<DOC><DOCNO> AP881215-0206 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-88 2155EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0737LeasingViolatedAntitrustAct12-15 0562</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0737,0574</SECOND><HEAD>Fierce Winds, Snow Hit California</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `The high pressure ..., to delete erroneousreference to 50,000 Mohawk Plant utility customers.</NOTE><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Fierce winds ripped across Northern California and ice pelletsand snow fell in the central coastal area of the state Thursday,while up to 18 inches of snow fell in Colorado and Michigan's UpperPeninsula.   Northward winds in California were clocked at 102 mph earlyThursday atop Mt. Diablo about 40 miles east of San Francisco.Hurricane force winds are 74 mph or greater. The winds caused atleast one death, overturned trucks and cut power to more than440,000 electric customers.   Winds gusted to 67 mph at Travis Air Force Base and to 54 mph onthe Golden Gate Bridge in San Francisco.   One to 2 inches of wet snow fell in the higher elevations nearPaso Robles, Calif. Ice pellets and snowshowers were reported overthe Inland Hills of Santa Barbara County.   A snow advisory was in effect for the higher elevations of thesouthern California deserts through Friday.   Early Thursday, winds in northern Utah blew trailers off theirfoundations at Utah State University in Logan. Winds gusted to 105mph at Centerville, 84 mph at Logan and 74 mph at Hill Air ForceBase. The winds knocked out power to 50,000 electric customers.   The high pressure system that produced strong winds overCalifornia and Utah also brought wind gusts of up to 65 mph at theNiagara Mohawk Power Plant in western New York and to 48 mph atSyracuse N.Y.   In Michigan's Upper Peninsula, up to 18 inches of snow fell.   ``Walloped? Who's been walloped?'' said Kerry Noble, manager ofABC True Value Hardware in Marquette. ``This is just a little(storm).''   In Colorado, six to 12 inches of snow was reported in theColorado Springs area with 2 feet snow drifts. Up to 18 inches werereported in the eastern foothills, 13 inches in west Denver, 11 inBoulder, 9 in Fountain, 6 in Pueblo, 3 in Trinidad and 2 in Lamar.   Cold arctic air kept Thursday afternoon temperatures below zeroover portions of northern Minnesota. Wind chill temperatures of 20to 40 below zero were common over the northern Plains and UpperMississippi Valley.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 8degrees below zero at Thief River Falls, Minn., to 81 degrees atBrownsville, Texas.   The low in the nation Thursday morning was 23 degrees below zeroat Park Rapids, Minn.   For Friday, the National Weather Service forecast light snow fromeastern North Dakota to portions of the Great Lakes region. Widelyscattered rainshowers will occur over northern and central Florida,southern California and southwest Arizona. Snowshowers will developover northern Arizona, southern Utah and in the mountains of Nevadaand California.   High temperatures will be in the teens from Minnesota to NewYork, with single digits and teens over northern New England. Highswill be in the 40s and 50s from South Carolina across the GulfCoastal states to much of Texas and New Mexico and in portions ofArizona, California, Oregon and Washington.   Highs in the 60s and 70s are expected in the Florida Peninsula,southern Arizona and coastal California. For much of the rest of thenation, highs will be in the 20s and 30s.</TEXT></DOC>